TextBlock.TextLine: I have severall letters of late recd. from m. whitley from madmarg
essost & from mft which mee thincks is most the same all
bending for mony be longing to yd brothers Josephs estate truely this
people either mustrust mee or never heard of selling goods tshould
be badd enough in case I could sell here for ready mony & make aso of
their mony, where as to the contrary wee sell upon time & in this
winter season mony is scarey & thought I remitt now & then
itt comes ny as yett this day £74„ 1„3 yett all that is nothing, last
week £50:& ordered G6 to draw £100 my desire is you would have
don to mee butt for my part to disbours & pay the mony before itt
comes in I shall not resolve I have send the acctt. curitt itt may bo
they will scruple, because I dend not those of sales & the reason
1s that I have had so much a do to ballance my hookes & ben d every
their acctt. that I delayd that till last for I have butt one wright
hem that writes english & my people can not do itt besides god
bethanked I have dayly some sale, so that our goods go pretty cleare
off & wish those att Hull: here you make no mention if any
beshipped of which I long to know whilst I remainee
London George Cole
In Antwerp 11 feb81
th
S. my last to you was on the 4 curitt with a remise for £50: & ondrto
draw one tam houndredpound more for acctt. of the estat of my: viviun
diseabed besides which do remitt here inclosed £74:1:3 att the charge
of John mertins 2 uso which cost 35:5 so please to give mee credat
accordingly & procure the ned full for the one & the other now have
have before mee yd of 28 past, I finde to be true that the pertutio
acctt is not charged with the charges att hull on the 6 bales you
mention, so must alow £5:17:1 for my ½part which shall
bedon accordingly you desire meets permitt you to draw on mee
£500 to give the retations forme satisfaction: I you please to
nate that I would do all I can to do you & them my service, yett
that I must refus & desire yd excuse for I do not to accept more
then what I can pay, besides I avoid as much as I can to accept balls
where fore keep rather not a farthing in my purse & remitt then
accept & afthought you supose that I shall have more mony in
hand then that should come to before the bills shall bedue gett
plaiuly shall accepted non butt the £100, that I desire you to draw
which with this & formar remise is neare ½ of the £500: you
desire & perhaps in less then aronth I'll remist the rest
for you must know I press my people more then heretefore
thought much against my honnour onely because I can not
abide to see such mistrusting letters so which in closed an answer
which pleases to deliver- by the by must accquaent you, which
you may keep to yd sel f & D.V. that I am overseere in thee tatt
off a broather in Law op mine D. bustt hop to whom is remitted
1690 bj will depeyster a bill of £80 druwe by Damil vivian
on Jeane, & protested att due time & retur. for pay for which
never a frating recouared neither had acy every my order to comrose
for the valew now the opphan is left alone findemy self in
in consoieus obliged toaccquant you that & give mee yd advise for
I well not for my part the valew of one farting formy sel ff butt
en dhe en consenne venge ae declrede ran
is not all to be recoueder att least I shall have that satisfaction
to have accquainted such an affare to you that will do formee
as for ijd self & so remon

London Gabriell Whitldy
In Antwerp 15 fe8 168
S I finde with mee yd of 20: past the contents I understand & referre
you in answer to mr. Cole & asseure you that god be thanked I have no
needof mr. Jos. vivian de ceased mony, wherefore tould wish you woud
be confident, that I never keep a forting of theirs on hand, butt
Rematt als soone as possible Im gett itt in of whch exspectner
desire not therrdwardt then what was allored mee when ealive
& charged to acctt. the ciritt beeng sent & some of sals wanting
shall follow p first, with a demonstration wheres & in whes
handis the mony standt out for though I finde to have todo
with in credible or mustrun belatius gett shwell vatgo mij
self & will ing give alle condeit that com bee exspect from
myrcaspnoble man & sorest

mad I finde a few lines from you which I sought to answer
large butt beeng willing to trouble you with much readrecg desire
you please to bereferred to m. George colo & mr. Gal whitley as
also to mr. Abram vivian & in case that can not be suffidient
lett any of the kerres of m. Jos: vivan come over & I shall give so
cefactiny what shall be in cash & assigne the rest by those wher itt is
lett p then endeavour to see if they will prevaile more then germable
to do the capital or estate is not in readg mony in handes, butt creditted
out in goods up on time truely I thought I did much that I disposed se
leverly of the goods & now mony comes in dayly butt in case the goods
had not been sold yetters now I have full goods of the liko sortimsold
want reason should there be to blame mee of to make suck hiscoried
of my punctuallitie I have onely to ad, that you may be confiden
that Ill do all I can togett int hedebto yrostiest
